@10047   = ~Narfell, an Empire of Ghosts~
@10048   = ~Narfell, an Empire of Ghosts 

Once, Narfell was a thriving empire under Nentyarch of Tharos, who conquered and united the surrounding kingdoms between -970 DR and -946 DR. At its zenith, the Nar Empire extended beyond its current borders of Lake Ashane in the east and the Giantspire Mountains in the west, and included much of Thesk, the Great Dale, and part of Thay. Though the emperor held titular authority, the real power in the Nar Empire was held by the priests, who enlisted the armies of demon lords through blood rituals. Perhaps their power was spread too thin, or perhaps their arrogance too great, because in the Year of Clipped Wings, -623 DR, the Nar's simultaneous invasions of both Unther and Mulhorand ended in epic failure. This failed attempt at expanding the empire weakened it substantially, making it an attractive target for the Raumathari Empire. The Year of the Stone Giant, -160 DR, found both empires locked in a war that would last for decades and decimate the population of both realms. Narfell's demon lords were not enough to save it. Both empires were crushed, and their inhabitants scattered.

Narfell's displaced survivors might have sworn to rebuild the empire, but it never came to pass. Too much had been lost to ever be regained. Now, the Nar peoples exist as barbarian tribes, merely trying to survive the next winter. Narfell's glorious history is reduced to tattered shreds of legend, and its majectic cities are no more than haunted ruins scattered across the cold, harsh landscape.~
@10049   = ~The Great Rift, Home of the Gold Dwarves~
@10050   = ~The Great Rift, Home of the Gold Dwarves 

The Great Rift is said to be part of the Shining South, though more accurately, one might say that the geographical region is the Great Rift and the underground nation within it is the Deep Realm. The Deep Realm is a fully autonomous monarchy ruled from the capital city of Underhome. It is inhabited mostly by gold dwarves, a striking sub-race of dwarves with darkened skin, gold or yellow hair, and amber-colored eyes. Gold dwarves tend to be more conservative than their shield dwarf cousins, and involve themselves little with outsiders, even those that live on the surface of their own country. Those of the Great Rift's million inhabitatns who do not live in the Deep Realm are shield dwarves, gnomes, and a few humans in the city of Khôltar.~
@10051   = ~A Wee Book of Riddles~
@10052   = ~A Wee Book of Riddles

I am rarely sought, but always found.
I reward all with equal measure.
I am the adventurer's constant companion, though all seek to avoid me.
I might be cheated, but I cannot be denied.
I am called terrible, though I am not always feared.
In the end, I will find you.
What am I?


Thy feet touch mine, but thy head touches me not.
I am fickle indeed, and will desert thee in the darkest places.
Thy height may be fixed, but mine is not.
I wear thy shape, but look little like thee.
What am I?


One can give of me freely and be called wise, yet squander me and be a fool.
A price is often fixed to me, yet no coin will buy more.
Often I have value only after I have fled.
I am invisible and intangible, yet no creature exists without me.
A person can take many, but still have only one.
What am I?


Old men boast of possessing me, yet I am no man's exclusive right.
By having less of me, one often gains more of me, though the gift is seldom welcome.
I am possessed most by those who need me least.
I am often claimed, but seldom understood.
I may exist in solitude, but I only gain worth when shared.
Those who need me most seldom appreciate me.
What am I?


A thing may be full of me, and still hold nothing.
I am made only by taking something else away.
When the wind blows across me, I can make a pleasant sound.
A man may make me wide and deep, and still I will have no substance.
What am I?


I am water and salt, but I am not the sea.
I am born of both sorrow and joy.
I am often restrained, but the loosing of me brings relief.
What am I?


I spring unbidden, yet I may be summoned by another.
I am often invoked, yet I am seldom welcome when I appear.
Held in check, I am resented by the bearer, released, I am resented by the object of my existence.
I am born of love, but I poison the thing that created me.
What am I?


I was born in a field, where I grew tall and slender.
I was cut down in my prime and beaten with sticks until I was broken.
I was cast between two stones and ground down to almost nothing.
I was drowned in water, and pounded with roughened fists.
I was left alone for a time, but when I had begun to rise up, I was thrown into a casket and roasted in the fire.
When I emerged, I was broken into many pieces and utterly consumed.
What am I?


Give up?

Death, Thy shadow, Life, Wisdom, A hole, Tears, Jealousy, Grain~
@10053   = ~Nanny Lu's Book of Limericks~
@10054   = ~Nanny Lu's Book of Limericks

In a castle that had a deep moat
A maid to her lover, she wrote.
To her, he came,  
But left, to his shame
'Cause he hadn't remembered a boat.


There once was a man of great deeds
Who thought first of all others' needs.
And when his turn came, 
His horse pulled up lame,
By the roadside, he sat in the weeds.


There was a young girl slim and fair
With long tresses of pale golden hair.
She brushed it at night
'Til it gleamed in the light,
Then she cut it all off on a dare.


There once was a Lantanese gnome
Whose husband was eager to roam.
She'd wait by the door
'Til she'd stand it no more.
Returning, he'd find no one home.


There once was a lad fair and randy
Always with lies quick to bandy.
To turn a maid's head,
Or get into her bed, 
Then out through a door that was handy.


There once was a gullible lass 
Who lived in a house made of glass,
With curtains, 'tis true,
But all could see through,
And chuckle a bit as they pass.~
